.TH Algae 1 "VERSION_DATE" "Version VERSION_NUMBER"
.SH NAME
algae \- another matrix programming language
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B algae
.RB [ "\-DhinpRrSsVx" ] " " [ "\-d num" ] " " [ "\-e script" ]
[ \fIfilename \&...\fR ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I algae
is an interpreter for the Algae programming language.  This language
provides a technical computing environment for numerical analysis.
.PP
This entry describes only how to run
.I algae;
see the manual (either printed or on-line) for information on the Algae
language, the standard functions, the data types, etc.  At
\fIalgae\fR's interactive prompt, type "help" to get the basics.
.PP
The input to
.I algae
is read from the list of files on the command line, or from standard
input if the list is empty.  Options are introduced with a hyphen,
except that a lone hyphen acts as a file name and refers to standard
input.
.SH OPTIONS
.I algae
has the following options:
.TP
.B \-D
turns on the disassembler, which prints \fIalgae\fR's opcodes in a form
like assembly language.  This is used for debugging the
.I algae
implementation.  You'll probably want to combine this with the
.B \-S
option.
.TP
.B \-di
sets the debug level to
.I i,
where
.I i
is an integer.  This is normally of use only for debugging the
.I algae
implementation.
.TP
.B \-e script
allows you to provide a script for
.I algae
to execute from the command line, rather than from a file or from
standard input.  Such a script is executed after any startup files but
before any other files are executed.  Any number of
.B \-e
options may be given, and the specified scripts are executed in the
order in which they appear on the command line.
.TP
.B \-h
prints a brief description of the command line arguments.
.TP
.B \-i
causes
.I algae
to use interactive mode when reading from the standard input device.
Without this option,
.I algae
uses interactive mode only when its input appears to be from a
terminal.  In interactive mode, input is parsed a line at a time
and exceptions do not cause
.I algae
to exit.
.TP
.B \-n
changes the way that scalars are displayed.  The printing statements
normally precede the scalar's value with a tab, and follow it with a
newline.  With this option set, neither the tab nor the newline is
printed.  (For character scalars, the quotation marks are also
omitted.)  This option affects the printing statements only, and has
no effect on the functions like printf.
.TP
.B \-p
enables execution profiling, a means for determining
the execution time characteristics of your Algae program.  When
profiling is enabled, the profiler periodically interrupts
.I algae
and records the line that is currently being executed.  When
.I algae
exits, it records this data in the file
.B algae.out
in the current directory.  Use the
.B prof
function to read the
.B algae.out
file and summarize it by file and by line number.

You may wish to use the
.B strip
function in conjunction with profiling.  Since
.B strip
removes the line and file information from a function, any time spent
in a call to that function gets charged to the line from which it was
called.

We've encountered several systems on which operating system bugs
prevent the execution profiler from working correctly.  These
include a DECstation and a Titan, both with MIPS architectures.
If you have such a system, then
.I algae
should have been installed with the execution profiler disabled.  In
that case, you'll get an error message if you try to use the
.B \-p
option.
.TP
.B \-R
causes \fIalgae\fR to run in restricted mode.  The
"system" function is disabled, as are "pipes".
.TP
.B \-r
forces
.I algae
to skip its command line editing and history facility.  This facility
is normally available, unless your version of
.I algae
was installed without it.  The editing commands are similar to Emacs:
forward (C-f), backward (C-b), up (C-p), and down (C-n).  You can
also change to
.I vi
style (M-C-j).
.TP
.B \-S
skips reading \fIalgae\fR's startup files.  This means that many of the
standard functions will be unavailable.
.TP
.B \-s
skips reading the user's startup file in
.B ~/.algae.
.TP
.B \-V
prints the version information.
.TP
.B \-x
causes \fIalgae\fR not to default to reading stdin when no file names
are given on the command line.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I algae.A
The system startup file for
.I algae.
Often located in the
.I /usr/local/lib
directory, its default name and path may be set to something different
during installation and they may be overridden with an environment
variable named ALGAE_RC0.  This file is not read if the
.B \-S
option is given.
.TP
.I ~/.algae
The user's startup file, normally read after
.I algae.A.
This file need not exist, and is skipped if either
.B \-S
or
.B \-s
option is given.  Its name may be overridden with the ALGAE_RC1
environment variable.
.TP
.I tools
A directory containing Algae files to define many of the standard
functions.  This is often named
.I /usr/local/lib/algae,
but its name is irrelevant so long as
.I algae.A
correctly identifies it.
.TP
.I algae.info
The on-line version of the manual (along with \fIalgae.info-1\fR,
\fIalgae.info-2\fR, etc.).  These should be in
.I /usr/local/info,
or wherever your Info reader expects them.
.SH BUGS
Bugs should be reported to ksh@sideslip.org.  See the "Bugs"
section of the manual for hints on how and when to report them.  A
list of known bugs is also given there.
